Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed with mental illness, and now she's making art on the subject - "Man should have the right to his own body"
Dozens of patient reports hang from the ceiling of the Project room at the Academy of Fine Arts.
They all have Camille Auer's name on them.
The papers tell a long story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Deciding for him who he is.
"I wanted to share my personal medical history so that the violence of the process would become visible," Auer says.
In the process, he refers to the gender correction process.
It is often a year-long research period that involves meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral to the diagnostic studies of "gender identity disorder", which are carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Before that, he had already used the estrogen he had ordered via the Internet and was already well advanced in his own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must undergo a correction process in order to be able to legally correct the gender.
Translaik, or transsek sualin sualin laitos (563/2002), obliges transgender people to undergo forced sterilization in order to get the right sex, for example, in the population register centre and passport.
At the moment, every sex corrector is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and evidence of reproductive incapacity.
You have the right to decide your own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," Auer said.
The reform of the Trans-Law has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight remarks on the law, and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect their sovereignty.
The previous Finnish Government prepared the amendment under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health, Susanne Huovinen.
There were elections and the Finns entered the government.
The law change is stuck again.
These are domestic political disputes that are not even related to this law.
“The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government regarding the amendment of the law,” said Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty International’s Finnish department.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of these consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient story installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by the psychologist of the transpole of Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on this, he wrote a report that would define Auer’s right to care and help.
The sense of reality to be studied is prone to vacillating.
The subject’s perception of self appears fragmented at the limit state level, and the unstable personality traits are emphasized.
Auer did not recognize himself in these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with mental illness," Auer says.
Even more shocking was when Auer was not given sex-correction treatment.
The nursing staff said his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the transpo lounge of the television.
Later on, that television produced a work of art called Monument for the Excluded, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that any woman at birth can enlarge her breasts, but a diagnosis is needed to remove the breasts," Auer said.
Your body is not yours if you feel that you are anything other than the number of your gender at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer’s experience is not the only one of its kind.
For many, the process of sexual correction is more difficult for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
The participants will meet dozens of people who need to justify their own existence and their right to their own sexual experience.
“It’s crazy for people who need support and help to be denied treatment on the grounds that they don’t have enough resources,” Auer said.
Many people who have applied to the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible experiences of bullying.
On the basis of these, medical staff may prescribe that treatment cannot be started.
“Preventing treatment and help can push a person into an even worse situation than it was before the process began,” Auer says.
Auer’s personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life, and that's something that people usually find difficult to digest."
The depression has been treated with medication, and when Auer started taking hormones, I felt better.
He had finally been able to express the feelings that had already existed in childhood and adolescence.
Why the wide chin didn’t seem to fit into your body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of flat.
The most important thing for Auer is that there are people around him who can see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using the voice and moving around," he says.
Today Auer feels already seen, she exists as a woman.
At the beginning of the process, however, random comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when people close to you are missexed.
“They should know and they know who I am, but they don’t agree or can’t internalize it,” he continues.
However, not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long research process, you cannot get official confirmation of your own sex.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination of the legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identification number, indicating that he or she feels that he or she is of the other sex.
After a six-month reflection period, the applicant will confirm his or her application in writing and the Ministry will give him or her a new personal identification number.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland, and the Auer exhibition also crystallises this requirement.
It has not been a therapeutic experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still plays a role and that it can bring about political change at a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
