Civil rights organization issued travel warning to Missouri
The National African-American Civil Rights Organisation (NAACP) has issued a travel warning for Missouri, due to discriminatory practices and racist attacks in the state.
“NAACP’s travel release for Missouri enters into force on August 28, 2017, urging African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling to a state that has recently witnessed a series of questionable racial events,” the organization said in a statement.
The recent law in Missouri makes it more difficult to bring discrimination cases to justice, and the state’s laws are disproportionately enforced against minorities, which, according to the NAACP, led to a travel warning.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They are being stopped on the basis of skin color and beaten or killed,” said Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri, to the Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of as many incidents in as short a time."
The Missouri travel bulletin is the organization’s first warning about the state of the United States.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. He was arrested by the Missouri police even though he was not charged with a crime.
According to the Missouri Attorney General, police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white driver.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be alert and to warn their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People need to prepare, for example, by taking money with them to pay bail or telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state.”
According to the FBI, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, the sixteenth largest in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU, an organization that defends constitutional civil rights, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws that oblige the police to arrest people for immigration violations, according to the organization, this will increase racial profiling.
While travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department and apply to other countries, they have recently been issued by NGOs in response to specific laws and developments in the United States.
