Hogan’s spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor’s actions in an interview with the Washington Post, saying it was merely a matter of moderation.
However, stigmatizing commentators as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to leaders of their choice, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors.
They told me that their comments were respectful, considerate and proper.
The pastor cited the Bible in his comment; he wanted to invoke Hogan’s Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani from Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile but asked a question about hate crimes.
