The governor's staff called the comments "a centralized attack," and someone else could call them "a centralized attack" to promote what they thought was important.
In the age of Facebook, communication is easy to control by blocking a reviewer or removing a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence demonstrators.
It’s the same thing, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be accused of chaining Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision on the matter was made last week in Virginia.
James C. Cacheris, a judge at the District Court of Alexandria, said the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution by blocking a voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Liberties Union went to discuss the use of Twitter and Facebook with Republican Governor Matt Bevin of Kentucky.
This shouldn't be difficult.
Low-cost postal charges in Washington had a similar effect to the Internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers haunted Washington.
There were trolls at the time.
The nicknames Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius and Portius wrote letters to the newspapers, defaming Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticising the Jay Agreement, a cooperation, trade and shipping agreement between the United States and the United Kingdom, as evidenced by documents collected by the Papers of George Washington web project.
He did not silence his critics.
Freedom of expression, freedom of opinion and freedom of debate are the foundations of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
