Bardina Degei doesn't cook with a stove.
He also rarely uses the pot.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, in the troubled province of Papua, Indonesia. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato – locally “nota” – directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the sweet potato burned on the crust is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
There is no furniture in Dege’s home; he sits on muddy ground, where he usually does his daily chores, such as laundry in cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is served by a bucket in the ceilingless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, and she has not been assigned to manage the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot.
“No one dares walk in the village after five in the evening,” Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse of everyday life in the Papuan Highlands, a former Dutch colony annexed to Indonesia in 1969, preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger to the Jakarta government, which holds firm control of the region and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, and the eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and rugged. The journey starts with a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapura, the capital of the province, to Nabir, and continues with a tumultuous five-hour drive in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
In the town of some 19,000 inhabitants, there are wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, whose corrugated ceilings have become yellow-brown with rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago tribesmen worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We didn't have these clothes," Degei explains. He means his colorful, hand-woven wrap cap, his dark skirt and his brightly colored blouse.
"Before, we only had leaves to cover our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's golden land.
Paniai is a highland region about the size of New Jersey, with 153,000 inhabitants. Just a hundred kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the world's largest and most lucrative gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, United States.
In 2015, the mine produced <0x24>3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
Papua also has an estimated <0x24>78 billion in timber reserves.
But for the Papuans, these riches bring misery, because they mean the repressive presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid nearly <0x24>20 million to local military personnel and military local units between 1998 and 2004, and as much as <0x24>150,000 to individual officers.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are being ruthlessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500,000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s became genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful protests.
The 2016 We Will Lose Everything report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane reports atrocities such as extrajudicial executions, torture — rape and electric shocks are particularly popular — and relentless attacks on peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of casualties because there are cases every week," said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
Screws have been tightened as Papua’s natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christian, but the demographics are changing as Indonesia’s populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi migrate to the region in the hope of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Javanese warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable blend in peanut sauce.
It’s hard for locals to compete.
“Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables on the market cheaper than locals,” says Abeth You, a 24-year-old from Pania who moved to the province’s capital for work.
"The local women lost their clients."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised in his 2014 election campaign to address injustices and human rights violations in Papua.
Papua consists of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Pania, on his way to the presidential castle in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokow in 2014 and waited for him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice,” You said.
Pania experienced some kind of wave bottom just two months after the inauguration of Jokow in October.
Eleven children were singing Christmas songs by a fire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014 when two Indonesian soldiers came out of the dark on motorcycles.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should use headlights.
One of the soldiers disliked the remark, but according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the reports of the victims and witnesses, the drunken soldiers seized the children and beat them with a rifle tail.
One of the soldiers shot at the children.
