When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic resonance images of the knee joints. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans. The assessment can be used to determine whether a person has entered puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I think that the method used is not the right one.
Determining the biological age in this way is highly uncertain.
If we can't determine the age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he told Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensics Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "Overall, it can be said that the risk of defining a child as an adult is low.
