"I think it's great to be able to look at a text written by a person who died more than 300 years ago," Rhodes said.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold the letter in my hand."
The Rhodes book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families living in Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, which was inspired by documents from the British National Library. The project was emotional.
"I was in tears when I noticed a thumbprint in a letter written by a double agent working for the Jacobites in the 18th century," Rhodes says.
It was his fingerprints.
And the letters smell of smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the smell makes the reader feel that he is on the spot.
I love the archives!”
With the support of the National Trust Foundation and the National Council for the Arts of England, the writer, who was attracted to the old documents, was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months, which seemed too good to be true.
He spent days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures, and rarities such as hyena heads hanging on the walls, and bottles that had been in the ditch for centuries.
He toured the ruins and lands of the old castle and talked with forest guards, gardeners and sometimes artists who illustrated the book.
In the evenings, he “takes a whiskey and starts writing.”
The closest history of Scotney is fairly unknown, as the castle was transferred entirely to the National Trust Foundation only after the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about a decade later, the Foundation’s staff was just beginning to review the archives. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking all the surpluses to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine land disputes being boring," Rhodes says. "However, here families even fought for one birch.
I thought we should let it go now.”
Some of the stories in the book go from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer. It tells the story of a man who, shortly after the completion of the castle, joins the English peasant revolt in 1381.
"The book Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex mentions a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes said.
"The English peasant revolt began in the same area, and it occurred to me that the revolt could begin with a riot.
“Maybe these events are related?”
Other stories in the book are closely related to the castle’s history—such as The Priest, the story of a priest that the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler, on the other hand, tells the story of smuggler Arthur Darrell from the 18th century, who is said to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (which was discovered years later when his grave was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. "The men in the family seem to have been quite a crook, they were constantly in debt and they were buying things they couldn't afford.
The men of the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women, and I see them as handsome guys who knew how to flatter heiresses."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Eläänmäki, a sanatorium in the early 20th century, from which only a eutrophicated plot remains.
The castle of Scotney has a special place in his heart.
“It was sad to leave,” he said.
“I didn’t want to go back to that damn thing.”
