Red Meat, Dairy Products and Chocolate May Alleviate Irritable Bowel Syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares in your digestive system.
However, a recent study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritated bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom. It causes stomach cramps, swelling, frequent or bleeding diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People suffering from irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that tryptophan, an essential amino acid in the protein, helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen bowel tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, who led the study, immune cells guard the gut and ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not enter the body.
Inflammatory cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance drops too close to the inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome may result.
In the experiments, immune cells that enhance tolerance were found in mice with specific bacteria in the intestines.
The bacterium in question needs tryptophan to start producing immune cells, which is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and the development of tolerance-promoting cells. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the gut," says Professor Colonna.
“The more tryptophan in mice’s diet, the more immune cells they had.”
If the same works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
Researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that while one group of mice had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same species, which were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiomes of mice, a normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the gut DNA of mice was examined, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells, but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria were given to mice that had grown in a sterile environment and did not have a gut microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how the bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquid and transplanted small amounts of fluid —without the bacteria— into immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into tolerability-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice’s diet, the number of cells that strengthen their tolerability increased by about 50%. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells decreased by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive system.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteri cause cells to develop in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been found in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
“We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the internal surfaces of the intestines,” says Cervantes-Barragan.
"High levels of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their proliferation."
